Tree basal area increment models for Cedrela, Amburana, Copaifera and Swietenia growing in the Amazon rain forests

Abstract

Little is known about sustainable forest management and tree growth in the Amazon forest. Reliable growth data from trees are very important in the context of forest management. Tree-characteristics such as architecture and competition are associated with diameter growth. Previous studies analyzing tree growth have indicated that these variables can describe these effects for temperate and boreal forests. However, the role of these effects for the growth of tropical trees needs to be enhanced for forest management practices. Here, we reconstructed the periodic annual basal area increment (BAIi cm2 yrâˆ’1) of four long-lived timber species from the Amazon forest of Brazil: (i) Cedrela odorata, (ii) Amburana cearensis, (iii) Copaifera pauper and (iv) Swietenia macrophylla to investigate the growth development. The study focuses on (i) drivers important for individual tree growth, (ii) calibration of an individual tree basal area increment model for each of the four species, and (iii) assessing the practical implementation of our findings for enhancing sustainable forest management of these four tree species in the Amazon rainforest. The results exhibit a significant relationship between increasing basal area increment versus increasing crown length and decreasing competition expressed by Hegyiâ€™s index. Trees sampled in densities greater than 25 m2 haâˆ’1 had their BAI% significantly reduced. For Cedrela an additional negative impact on basal area increment from liana load is evident. Our findings reinforce the importance of release trees to obtain better crown exposure.

1. Introduction

The Amazon forest in South America comprises one of the worldâ€™s largest biodiversity pools, and considerable efforts have been put in place to protect this forest. Nevertheless deforestation is still the major threat mainly because of the lack of knowledge in sustainable forest management (Godar et al., 2012).

The Brazilian Forest Service has established norms addressing sustainable forest management by ensuring biodiversity and conservation issues as well as providing saw-timber for commercial use (IBAMA, the agency responsible for forest policy and law enforcement, Normative Instruction 5, 2006). A practical guideline provides management practices by using a Minimum Cutting Diameter (MCD) of 50 cm, a cutting cycle of 25â€“35 years and an average reference increment rate of 0.86 m3 haâˆ’1 yrâˆ’1 for all commercial forest tree species. This regulation serves as a minimum harvesting requirement to avoid overcutting within the forest. It is important because the Amazon rainforest is comprised of a large number of tree species, but only some of them are of commercial interest for the timber industry (nowadays an average of 20 species are usually harvested).

The practical problem of these regulations is that no information on species-specific changes in volume growth over time is available which limits sustainable forest management. This may lead to over cuttings or even an exploitation of high value tree species within such forests even if the â€œincrement-reference-systemâ€ with a cutting cycle of 25â€“35 years (see IBAMA/Normative Instruction 5, 2006) is applied (SchÃ¶ngart, 2008). This suggests that a species-specific silvicultural management and controlling system is needed to ensure sustainable wood production but also to address conservation issues of the forests.

A first step is to enhance our understanding of the annual increment rates by tree species, site, as well as stand conditions and implement these findings in simple species specific growth models to guide the Amazon forest management.

In temperate forests, annual increment rates and thus tree and stand age, are easy to determine due to the distinct seasonality and the appearance of the tree rings. However, within rainforests, tree rings may follow a different pattern and therefore they may not be usable as a measure of annual growth rates (Lieberman and Lieberman, 1985). This makes the determination of annual increment rates by tree species and stand age much more difficult. Previous studies on individual tree-growth in the Amazon forest were questioned due to this problem (e.g. Lieberman and Lieberman, 1985), while recent research based on tree ring analysis has proven that annual tree rings exists for trees growing in the Amazon forest (Worbes, 1995). Tree rings are caused by the occurrence of a specific annual dry season (Brienen and Zuidema, 2005, SchÃ¶ngart, 2008). This change from a wet to dry season evokes changes in wood anatomy and wood density (early wood, late wood) and turn the tree-ring more visible allowing for a measure of the annual diameter or individual tree basal area increment rates (da Cunha, 2009, Fig. 1). Based on these findings, growth data collection and interpretation for developing growth models are possible for some trees of the Amazon forest.

Growth models predict tree growth over time based on relationships between increment rates and potential drivers. Commonly such drivers are crown attributes, as a surrogate for the assimilation surface of a tree (Hasenauer and Monserud, 1996), competition variables for determining the competitive situation of a given tree versus its neighbors (Monserud and Sterba, 1996), as well as site conditions (see Wykoff, 1990, Choi et al., 2001). While lots of such studies and growth models have been developed for temperate forests as part of a sustainable forest planning tool (Hasenauer, 2006, Cole and Lorimer, 1994) a lack of models fitted to predict tree-growth using tree-size variables is evident for tropical rainforests.

The objective of this study is to provide information related to individual tree growth for four long-lived commercial tree species growing in the Amazon rainforest: Cedrela odorata, Amburana cearensis, Copaifera paupera, and Swietenia macrophylla. We are specifically interested in (i) drivers important for individual tree growth, (ii) calibration of an individual tree basal area increment model for each of the four species, and (iii) assessing the practical implementation of our findings for enhancing sustainable forest management of these four tree species in the Amazon rain forest.

2. Materials and method

2.1. Study area and data collection

Data for this study came from Acre, a state in the western corner of Brazil located in the Amazon rainforest. Four Annual Production Units (APU) were selected to collect the data (Fig. 2). An APU is defined as an annual planning unit for harvesting within the following year. It has a size of up to 400 ha. Commonly 25â€“35 m3/ha are cut by removing trees â©¾50 cm in DBH (diameter at breast height). Since a so called â€œreference incrementâ€ â€“ defined with 0.86 m3/ha and a minimum DBH of 50 cm â€“ is required for cutting (see IBAMA/Normative Instructions 7, 2006) the harvesting interval of an APU is about 30 years.

Each of the available APU (Annual Production Units) presents semi-deciduous forests with a mean basal area of approximately 30 m2/ha and a mean height ranging between 30 and 35 m with some individuals reaching a top height of 45 m. The DBH can reach up to 2 m. The mean annual precipitation is 1800â€“2000 mm, with a mean annual temperature of 26 Â°C (Sombroek, 2001a, Sombroek, 2001b). From October to April strong rains are common, followed by three consecutive dry months. During these dry months (dry season peaks in July) the average rainfall is less than 50 mm per month (Sombroek, 2001a, Sombroek, 2001b). The dominant soils within the region are dystrophic oxisols with a high clay texture (Dâ€™Oliveira, 2000).

The four tree species selected for our study are: C. odorata; S. macrophylla; A. cearensis and C. paupera (hereafter referred to by genus only). The species belong to the group of major economic species in the region and are currently traded as timber. It is important to note that Swietenia has been added to the list of endangered species. Thus the harvest is only allowed under special conditions. Cedrela and Swietenia are leafless during the dry-season (July to September) and produce new leaves every year from October to November. According to Worbes, 1995, DÃ¼nisch et al., 2003, Brienen and Zuidema, 2005 annual tree rings are detectable for Cedrela, Amburana, Swietenia, and Copaifera, because trees show distinct growth periods, which are considered as annual tree-rings (Fig. 1).

2.2. Tree measurements

The tree data for this study were provided by a timber company and come from a forest inventory (Figueiredo et al., 2007). For each tree, the tree species, diameter at breast height and the tree location resulting from GPS measurements are available. Trees were selected according to the following criteria: (i) covering one of our four different tree species, (ii) range in DBH, (iii) social position to address differences in the light regime, and (iv) variation in the differences of the treeâ€™s competitive status. This resulted in 120 trees for Cedrela, 68 for Amburana, 70 for Copaifera and 45 for Swietenia carefully selected in order to cover the range of different development stages and growing conditions by species.

All the trees were grouped by DBH class at 20 cm intervals and localized and marked into the forest using a high-sensitivity GPS Sirf Star III technology. Each tree-coordinate was taken from the forest inventory map.

For each tree the DBH was recorded with a metric tape. Total tree height and height to the live crown base was recorded with an electronic hypsometer Vertex. Crown length is defined as the difference between total tree height and height to the live crown base. The crown diameter was measured in 8 directions and recorded with metric tape and a Suunto hypsometer to determine the vertical crown projection.

Crown Position Index (CPI), a measure for the light conditions of a tree within a stand (Davies et al. 1998), was recorded after modifying the classification of Dawkins (1963) to three light classes:

CPI 1 = emergent crown with direct light from above as well as lateral light;

CPI 2 = light from above the canopy, but no lateral light due to competition;

CPI 3 = no direct sun light.

The Crown Position Index (CPI) exhibits a good correlation with the canopy openness in non-managed native forests (Davies et al., 1998). Note that the CPI is not comparable with the common tree classification system for temperate and boreal forests proposed by Kraft (1884). The growth of trees in the Amazon rain forest depends not only on the light regime from above. It also is strongly driven by lateral incoming radiation. This is explicitly addressed with the CPI classification scheme.

The occurrence of liana load (LL) on a crown was recorded for each species to analyze potential effects of liana load on tree growth (Schnitzer and Bongers, 2002). The classification were done by using three groups:

LL1 â€“ trees with no liana or less than 50% covered in the crown;

LL2 â€“ 50â€“75% of the crown covered with liana;

LL3 â©¾ 75% of the crown is covered with liana.

2.3. Tree competition measures

Individual tree growth strongly depends on the level of competition which can be expressed by competition indices derived from routine inventory data. Competition measures define the competitive situation of a given tree within a stand for limited resources (light, water, nutrition, etc.) (TomÃ© and Burkhart, 1989). We assess the competitive status for each sampled tree using the concept of asymmetric competition (Schwinning and Weiner, 1998, Freckleton and Watkinson, 2001, Mitsuda et al., 2002). This approach defines a distance to an active competitors (Distij) of a subject tree (i) to those neighbors (j) whose total height (hi) is greater than an imaginary inclined line traced from the object treeâ€™s live crown base (hbci) with a 45Â° angle, defined as tan(45Â°) (see Fig. 3).

Every tree within the angle of a given subject tree is considered as an active competitor for that subject tree (see Fig. 3) and can be defined as:(1)tan45Â°=hj-hbciDistij=1â‡’(hj-hbci>Distij)

Next the competition situation for each of our selected sample trees was derived according to Hegyi (1974). This so called Hegyi index defines the relationship between the DBH from the competitor â€œjâ€ and the object tree â€œiâ€ weighted by the horizontal distance between the trees. We follow the suggestion by Sabatia and Burkhart (2012) who modified the formula by adding the exponent 0.5 to the distance:(2)Hegyi=âˆ‘j=1nDBHjDBHiÃ—Distij0.5

This index assumes that the competition effects of neighboring trees increases with increasing breast height diameter of the competitor (DBHj) and decreasing distance (Distij) between the subject tree â€˜iâ€™ and respective competitors â€˜jâ€™.

Stand density was assessed for each subject tree to determine the resulting impact on growth by using the concept of Density Point Measure (DPA). We compare the tree productivity with the competition and derive how a given competitive situation will affect tree growth. DPA is an angle sum method as proposed by Spurr (1962) and may be seen as a modified angle count method (Bitterlich, 1984), which considers that the mean basal area per hectare (BAâ€¾) can be calculated as:(3)BAâ€¾=âˆ‘i=inn-12Ã—DBHjDistij24nwhere n represents the number of selected competitor trees according to Eq. (1), DBHj is the diameter at breast height of the competitor, and Distij is the distance between the subject tree i and its competitor j.

2.4. Deriving individual tree growth

For each tree two increment cores (10 cm length and 5 mm width) were extracted at 1.3 m between July and October. If the trees exhibited tabular roots (â€œsapopemasâ€ common for Cedrela and Swietenia) the cores were extracted 30 cm above (Metcalf et al., 2008). The tree-ring growth was visually cross-dated using the increment cores (Stokes and Smiley, 1996) and the annual radial increment was recorded for the last 4 years to the nearest 0.01 mm by using Lintab II (Frank Rinn S.A. Heidelberg, Germany) and TSAP-Win software (Rinn, 2003). For this time period (four years) it was assumed that the canopy structure and competition within our forests was constant. Next we reconstructed the 4 year radial increment from the current DBH to derive the diameter increment (id) of the past four years and the previous diameter at breast height (DBH1) by subtracting id. With this information we can calculate the observed periodic mean average annual basal area increment for each tree (BAIi cm2 yrâˆ’1) of the last four years (Assmann, 1970):(4)BAIi=Ï€42Â·DBHiÂ·id+id24

The relative increment of each tree (BAI%) can be derived as(5)BAI%=BAIi(BA2+BA1)2âˆ—100where BAIi is the 4 year basal area increment BA1 the basal area at the beginning and BA2 the basal area at the end of the 4 year growing period. This procedure will allow an approximation of the time required to produce the target diameter for cutting (Wadsworth et al., 2010).

2.5. Construction of a tree basal area increment model

To assess the potential drivers of individual tree growth we started with an explorative data analysis seeking simple drivers by a correlation analysis ran between our tree basal area increment (BAI) versus (i) tree-size variables, (ii) competition measures, and (iii) the liana load. This correlation was plotted to permit graphical assessment of the species specific association among the variables and to formulate the following general individual tree basal area increment model:(6)ln(BAI)=a+biÃ—(Treesize)+ciÃ—(Comp)+diÃ—(LL)where the ln(BAI) is the natural logarithm of the four year basal area increment from each tree, a is the intercept, bi is the vector of coefficients for the tree size variables (Treesize), c is the vector of the coefficients for the tree competition measures (Comp), and d is the coefficient to evaluate the liana load effect (LL) on tree growth. Note that LL is used as a dummy variable and characterize the three LL groups.

The vector for Treesize includes the diameter at breast height (DBH), total tree height (h), crown diameter (cd), and crown length (cl). The vector for Comp comprises Hegyiâ€™s competition index (see Eq. (2)) and the Crown Position Index (CPI).

The results from Pearsonâ€™s correlations of BAIi versus the tree-size variables, (i) diameter at breast height (DBH), (ii) height (h), (iii) crown length (cl) and (iv) crown diameter (cd) revealed significant (Î± = 0.05) relationships for all trees species. The same procedure was applied for the individual tree competition measures according to (i) Hegyi index (see Eq. (2)), and (ii) the Crown Position Index (CPI). Finally the same procedure was applied to test whether or not liana load (LL) has any influence on tree growth. Note that no liana load was recorded for Amburana (Table 2).

3.2. Calibration of tree basal area increment models

The results of Table 2 provide the potential â€œdriversâ€ to calibrate a basal area increment model for each tree species according to Eq. (6) by species. All variables selected had to be significant at Î± = 0.05. Multicollinearity was controlled by requiring a variance inflation factor (VIF) to be less than 5 for each predictor variable. The VIF for the ith regression coefficient is simply the ith diagonal element of the inverse of the correlation matrix (Snee, 1973) and represents the increase in the variance due to the correlation between the predictors (Marquardt, 1970, Van Laar, 1991). A large VIF (e.g. >5) indicates a strong correlation between certain predictor variables. This situation can produce misleading results because it does not provide adequate independent information for reliable predictions (Snee, 1973). We employed multiple linear regressions using PROC REG to calculate the variance inflation factor VIF of the independent variables (SAS Institute Inc., 2009). For each tree species we started with the full set of variable and removed one variable after the other, each with a separate regression run, if either Î± > 0.05 or if VIF > 5. This resulted in species-specific increment functions.

BAIi data exhibit increasing variance with tree-size variables therefore the coefficients of the final models were calibrated using a Gamma distribution (e.g. Gea-Izquierdo and CaÃ±ellas, 2009, Contreras et al., 2011). After retransforming Eq. (6) in its nonlinear form the Gamma distribution enables us to directly model the selected dependent variable by avoiding a potential bias of the transformed models (Table 3). Crown length and Hegiys competition index entered the model significantly. Only for Cedreala Liana Load (LL2, and LL3), used as a dummy variable, additionally entered the individual tree basal area increment model.

3.3. Management implications

An important task of the study is to provide practical solutions for implementing sustainable forest management options for our four investigated tree species. The Crown Position Index (CPI) (Dawkins, 1963), did not enter the basal are increment equations significantly (see Table 3). For each tree species the BAI (tree basal are increment) differs by CPI (social position), and DBH class (Fig. 6). The MCD (Minimum Cutting Diameter) according to the Brazilian forest law (IBAMA/Normative Instruction 5, 2006) requires a DBH â©¾ 50 cm.

The response to crown release differs by the competitive situation of a tree within a stand (Fig. 6). Thus we were interested in assessing the productivity potential and the time required in achieving a certain target diameter e.g. the MCD (Minimum Cutting Diameter) by obtaining the results of Eq. (3) for assessing the productivity potential PBAIi in percent defined as:(7)PBAIi(%)=BAIi/BAiÂ·100where BAIi the tree basal area increment from Eq. (3) and BAi the tree basal area of the subject tree at the beginning of the growth period.

Our data covered a wide variety of stand density situations so we are interested in the confidence interval or â€œcorridorâ€ of our species-specific growth functions. The confidence interval CI for the mean of the differences D (predicted âˆ’ observed) can be used to evaluate discrepancies between the expected difference and the estimator Dâ€¾ (Reynolds, 1984):(8)CI=Dâ€¾Â±SDnÂ·t1-Î±/2,(n-1)where Dâ€¾ is the mean, SD the standard deviation of the Di differences, n is the sample size and t is the 1 âˆ’ Î±/2 quantile of the t-distribution with n âˆ’ 1 degrees of freedom.

For practical silvicultural decision making one of the key questions is the time it takes to grow a given tree from a certain starting diameter to an expected target diameter. With the results of the regression analysis (Table 3) the four year increment rates according to tree and competition attributes are predictable for each tree within a stand. With this information we can estimate the number of years (t) required to grow a given tree with a basal area corresponding to a DBH = 30 cm (BAi) to the basal area of a tree with a DBH = 50 cm (BAi+1) by obtaining the relative increment rates (PBAI%) of Eq. (7). This procedure follows the compound interest law as proposed by Schneider and Schneider (2008) and can be expressed as:(9)BAi+1=(1+PBAI%)tÂ·BAiâˆ´t=ln(BAi+1)-ln(BAi)ln(1+PBAI%)where ln is the natural logarithm and all other variables are as previously defined. Again the confidence interval was calculated to express the range for future predictions (Table 5).

The access to direct sunlight expressed by a crown position index of 1 (CPI = 1) is essential to enhance tree growth and thus reaching the Minimum Cutting Diameter (MCD = 50 cm) for harvesting within a minimum time e.g. the lowest number of years for growing a tree from 30 to 50 cm in DBH (Table 5). From a practical forest management perspective a simple relationship between tree competition (e.g. Crown Position Index â€“ CPI) and forest density is required. Thus we obtain the estimated relative potential productivity (Eq. (7)) for each tree and group them in 5 forest density classes: <10 m2 haâˆ’1, 10â€“15, 16â€“20, 21â€“25, and >25 m2 haâˆ’1). We did not separate our results by tree species because the Brazilian Forest Service also uses only general forest density measures (IBAMA/Normative Instructions 5, 2006) (Fig. 7). The Tukeyâ€“Kramer test revealed a significant reduction in mean productivity if the basal area and thus forest density is â©¾25 m2 haâˆ’1.

4. Discussion

The best predictor variables for tree growth of Cedrela odorata, Amburana cearensis, Copaifera paupera, and Swietenia macrophylla, for important commercial tree species growing in the Amazon rain forests, are the (i) crown length, and the (ii) Hegyi index, a measure for individual tree competition (Fig. 3, Table 2). The only exception is C. odorata where liana load is an additional driver for individual tree basal area increment (Table 3).

Cedrela, Copaifera and Swietenia exhibit a similar behavior between BAI (tree Basal Area Increment) vs. Crown Length while the BAI crown length development of Amburana is much more sensitive to changes in crown length (Fig. 4 left). BAI vs. Hegyiâ€™s competition index (Fig. 4 right) exhibits an exponential decline with increasing competition following a similar pattern for all four tree species. Hegyiâ€™s competition index (Hegyi, 1974) was originally developed for pure uniform stands. According to our results we show that this concept is also applicable for trees growing in mixed species stands of the Amazon rain forest.

The species-specific growth parameters for deriving basal area increment show the differences in the shade tolerance of the species. This is important for assessing the impact of the selected drivers (crown length, Hegyi index, liana load) on BAI (Fig. 4, Fig. 5). From these figures we conclude that Cedrela grows better no matter of the light situation since at a given competition situation (e.g. Hegyi index) higher BAI are evident as compared to all other tree species. It is followed by Swietenia, Copaifera, and Amburana, which exhibit a more sensitive behavior in BAI vs. decline in crown length. Our results are consistent with previous findings by Walters et al., 2005, Rigamonte-Azevedo et al., 2006.

Cedrela additionally exhibits a decline in BAI with increasing liana load: LL1 (no liana load) differs significantly from LL2 (up to 50% liana load) and LL3 (more than 50% liana load) (see Fig. 5). These results are consistent with findings of Putz, 1984, Clark and Clark, 1990, Ladwig and Meiners, 2009, Ingwell et al., 2010. They have also proven that a decline in tree growth with increasing liana load is evident. Kainer et al. (2006) concluded in their study that the liana load might have a weak or even no effect on diameter growth of tropical trees.

Amburana, Copaifera and Swietenia are light demanding tree species. Therefore small individuals growing in shady conditions (size 10â€“30 cm of DBH and CPI 3) are difficult to find and they are underrepresented in our data set (Fig. 6).

An important task in sustainable forest management is to predict the growth of different tree species relative to site and stand density conditions (see Eq. (3)). This information will be transferred to simple management guidelines only if it is available (Fig. 6 and Table 4, Table 5). We are able to provide and thus ensure sustainable forest management strategies for tree species growing in the Amazon rain forest. As shown in Fig. 6 for each tree species BAI (Basal Area Increment) varies by DBH class (diameter at breast height) and CPI (Crown Position Index). With increasing social position (CPI 1 = direct light) BAI increases with increasing DBH class until DBH class 70â€“90 where a plateau. We can also demonstrate that if light availability declines (see CPI 2 and CPI 3 vs. CPI 1) at the same DBH lower BAI is evident for all tree species. Forest stands with limited lights also show that the light demanding tree species Amburana, Copaifera, and Swietenia only partly grow under intermediate (CPI = 2) but do not grow under suppressed (CPI 3) stand conditions (see Fig. 6). The only exception is the shade tolerant species Cedrela, where for intermediate light conditions (CPI 2) trees are also growing across all DBH classes, while for suppressed trees (CPI 3) only in young DBH classes some tree were detectable (see Fig. 6). The performed Tukey Kramer test exhibited significant differences between CPI 1 and all other classes (see Fig. 5).

High productivity was evident for all species with enough available light (Table 4). For example a Cedrela tree with a DBH of 30 cm and a crown in full light conditions (above and lateral, CPI 1) showed a production rate of 6.1%. When the light condition changes to no direct sun light in the crown (CPI 3, see Table 5) a tree with a DBH of 30 cm will need approximately 19 years more to reach 50 cm in DBH. This attribute has important implications in the timber production. In this way Brienen and Zuidema (2006), emphasizes the technical benefits and the economic viability of tree liberation activity to improved future yield of the forest.

From a practical purposes the results of Table 4, Table 5 are important since the relative annual basal area increment by species in tree growth are provided. Productivity starts to decline at a basal area of about 20â€“25 m2 haâˆ’1 and significantly falls off at >25 m2 haâˆ’1 (Fig. 7). This density range suggests that stand density should be kept at this or below this basal area to ensure the highest growth rates. Our findings confirm the results of Wadsworth et al. (2010). In their practical guidelines a stand density of approximately 25 m2 haâˆ’1 is suggested.

The current forest management regulations of the Amazon rain forest were established by the Brazilian Forest Service and require a Minimum Cutting Diameter (MCD) of 50 cm, a cutting cycle of 25â€“35 years and a reference increment of 0.86 m3/ha/yr (IBAMA/Normative Instruction 5, 2006). If we compare our findings with the current management guidelines we can conclude that under optimal light conditions Cedrala exhibits the highest growth rates and depending on the Crown Position Index 17 years (CPI 1), 19 years (CPI 2) and 36 years (CPI 3) are needed so that a tree grows from 30 to 50 cm. Swietenia needs 22 (CPI 1), and 37 years (CPI 2) while Amburana and Copaifera require approximately 25â€“28 (CPI 1), and 36â€“30 years (CPI 2) (Table 5) in reaching the Minimum Cutting Diameter (MCD) of 50 cm. Our study confirms that the current forest management guidelines and regulation applied in the Amazon rain forest (IBAMA/Normative Instruction 5, 2006) are conservative but correct estimates and ensure sustainable harvesting.
